        <b><span id="titleLabel">2.4 - The next frontier in funding: How hedge funds, foreign money, and nontraditional financing are creating opportunity for game makers</span></b>
        <table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="dateTimeLabel">Wednesday, May 10, 3:30 PM - 5:00 PM</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="roomLabel">Room 406AB</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="descriptionLabel">Funding creativity has never been easy, but that hasn't stopped the flow of money toward game developers and game-related business models. Over the past year, a number of new game studios and hybrid development models have been announced. Trilogy Studios tapped independent equity funding, BioWare/Pandemic secured hedge money from Elevation Partners, and a number of online game developers continue to ride the wave of VC money flowing into their coffers. This session will focus on new funding models as well as the state of traditional funding. Listen as a panel of knowledgeable investors and recently funded game studios discuss where to locate private funding, venture capital, hedge fund investment, and foreign investors. What are investors looking for? What should you expect from Asian publishers who are funding games from the West? And what does it take to attract hedge fund backing? This session will also look at which genres are most likely to get funded, how current deals are set up, who the most aggressive funders are today, and what amounts of money are most commonly advanced.</span></td>
            </tr>
